{"title_page": "Andrew Lee (entrepreneur)", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| embed          = \n| name           = Andrew Lee\n| title          = Crown Prince of Korea\n| titletext      = \n| more           = \n| type           = \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        =\n\n| succession     = \n| moretext       = \n| reign          = \n| reign-type     = \n| coronation     = \n| cor-type       = \n| predecessor    = \n| pre-type       = \n| successor      = \n| suc-type       = \n| regent         = \n| reg-type       =\n\n| succession1    = \n| moretext1      = \n| reign1         = \n| reign-type1    = \n| coronation1    = \n| cor-type1      = \n| predecessor1   = \n| pre-type1      = \n| successor1     = \n| suc-type1      = \n| regent1        = \n| reg-type1      =\n\n| succession2    = \n| moretext2      = \n| reign2         = \n| reign-type2    = \n| coronation2    = \n| cor-type2      = \n| predecessor2   = \n| pre-type2      = \n| successor2     = \n| suc-type2      = \n| regent2        = \n| reg-type2      =\n\n| succession3    = \n| moretext3      = \n| reign3         = \n| reign-type3    = \n| coronation3    = \n| cor-type3      = \n| predecessor3   = \n| pre-type3      = \n| successor3     = \n| suc-type3      = \n| regent3        = \n| reg-type3      =\n\n<!-- succession4 to succession9 are also available -->\n\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = <!-- For Gregorian dates: {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| birth_place    = [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place    = \n| burial_date    = \n| burial_place   = \n| spouse         = Princess Nana Lee\n| spouse-type    = \n| consort        = <!-- yes or no -->\n| issue          = Two children\n| issue-link     = \n| issue-pipe     = \n| issue-type     = \n| full name      = \n| era name       = \n| era dates      = \n| regnal name    = \n| posthumous name= \n| temple name    = \n| house          = [[House of Yi]]\n| house-type     = \n| father         = Jay Lee\n| mother         =\n\n| religion       =\n| occupation     = Entrepreneur, software developer\n| signature_type = \n| signature      =\n\n| module         = \n}}\n'''Andrew Lee''' is an American entrepreneur, software developer, writer and Korean Crown Prince. He is the founder of the [[VPN]] service [[Private Internet Access]], which started in 2010.<ref>https://proprivacy.com/vpn/privacy-news/an-interview-with-private-internet-access-founder-andrew-lee</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/29/californian-techie-becomes-korean-crown-prince-fairytale-twist</ref> In 2018 [[Yi Seok]], son of Prince Yi Kang, the fifth son of [[Emperor Gojong]], nominated him as a Crown Prince of Korea as a descendant of the [[House of Yi]], the last ruling royal house of Korea during the [[Joseon dynasty]]. Following his nomination of Crown Prince, he announced plans to launch an investment fund for Korean entrepreneurs and establish a free coding school in Korea.\n\nHe also co-founded Mt. Gox Live which was acquired by Japan-based [[Mt. Gox]], then the world's leading Bitcoin exchange, and built their official mobile application. Mt. Gox closed in 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nLee was born and raised in Indianapolis, he says his parents never disclosed their royal relations, so he only learned about his connection through a passing reference from a relative. His father provided him with a computer when he was a child, which began interest in the internet, and he learning more about it through meeting people online on [[IRC]] chat rooms. He enrolled in [[Purdue University]] and transferred to [[University at Buffalo]], but eventually dropped out of school to start work on the internet.\n\nAndrew began his career as one of the two original System Administrators of AcmeShells.com, a major [[UNIX]] shell provider. After the company was acquired, he moved to Telemon and finally joined National Honey Almond, Inc (Blunt Wraps, Bluntville Cigars). While at NHA, as the [[Brand Manager]], He helped establish Bluntville as the best selling [[cigar]] on the East Coast.\n\nIn 2009, he built London Trust Media, Inc. LTM, a private holdings company. Lee founded Private Internet Access in 2010, which is the largest brand owned by London Trust Media.<ref>https://lifeboat.com/ex/bios.andrew.lee</ref> PIA was started because of Lee's interest in IRC, in order to protect one's [[IP address]] from exposure using an [[IRC bouncer]]. Eventually after being exposed to different industries, he realized it was time for internet privacy to go mainstream.<ref>https://www.linuxjournal.com/content/fight-control-andrew-lee-open-sourcing-pia</ref>\n\nHe also cofounded and sold many startups. One of his bitcoin ventures includes Mt. Gox North America, Inc., which was acquired by Tibanne Co. Ltd. in early 2011.\n\nAndrew contributes to online publications. Including FOL which is the online magazine of [[Rick Falkvinge]], the founder of the [[Pirate Party]].\n\nA few years before 2018 Lee met Emperor Yi Seok and the two got along so well Yi Seok decided to make him prince. A  \u201cpassing of the sword\u201d was held at the Crustacean Beverly Hills, a high-end Vietnamese seafood restaurant in Los Angeles. \u201cI will commit to the values of love, human rights, peace and freedom for humanity to the best of my ability,\u201d Lee swore on a [[ceremonial sword]]. Attendees included officials from [[Jeonju]], the family's ancestral home; Los Angeles city council members [[David Ryu]], [[Nury Martinez]] and [[Marqueece Harris-Dawson]]; and [[Bermuda]] Premier [[David Burt]].<ref>https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/andrew-lee-named-new-korean-crown-prince-300731986.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:House of Yi]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Bitcoin]]\n[[Category:Korean investors]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Las Vegas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| embed          = \n| name           = Andrew Lee\n| title          = Crown Prince of Korea\n| titletext      = \n| more           = \n| type           = \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n\n| succession     = \n| moretext       = \n| reign          = \n| reign-type     = \n| coronation     = \n| cor-type       = \n| predecessor    = \n| pre-type       = \n| successor      = \n| suc-type       = \n| regent         = \n| reg-type       = \n\n| succession1    = \n| moretext1      = \n| reign1         = \n| reign-type1    = \n| coronation1    = \n| cor-type1      = \n| predecessor1   = \n| pre-type1      = \n| successor1     = \n| suc-type1      = \n| regent1        = \n| reg-type1      = \n\n| succession2    = \n| moretext2      = \n| reign2         = \n| reign-type2    = \n| coronation2    = \n| cor-type2      = \n| predecessor2   = \n| pre-type2      = \n| successor2     = \n| suc-type2      = \n| regent2        = \n| reg-type2      = \n\n| succession3    = \n| moretext3      = \n| reign3         = \n| reign-type3    = \n| coronation3    = \n| cor-type3      = \n| predecessor3   = \n| pre-type3      = \n| successor3     = \n| suc-type3      = \n| regent3        = \n| reg-type3      = \n\n<!-- succession4 to succession9 are also available -->   \n\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = <!-- For Gregorian dates: {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| birth_place    = [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], [[United States]]\n| death_date     = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place    = \n| burial_date    = \n| burial_place   = \n| spouse         = Princess Nana Lee\n| spouse-type    = \n| consort        = <!-- yes or no -->\n| issue          = Two children\n| issue-link     = \n| issue-pipe     = \n| issue-type     = \n| full name      = \n| era name       = \n| era dates      = \n| regnal name    = \n| posthumous name= \n| temple name    = \n| house          = [[House of Yi]]\n| house-type     = \n| father         = Jay Lee\n| mother         = \n\n| religion       =\n| occupation     = Entrepreneur, software developer\n| signature_type = \n| signature      = \n\n| module         = \n}}\n'''Andrew Lee''' is an American entrepreneur, software developer, writer and Korean Crown Prince. He is the founder of the [[VPN]] service [[Private Internet Access]], which started in 2010.<ref>https://proprivacy.com/vpn/privacy-news/an-interview-with-private-internet-access-founder-andrew-lee</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/12/29/californian-techie-becomes-korean-crown-prince-fairytale-twist</ref> In 2018 [[Yi Seok]], son of Prince Yi Kang, the fifth son of [[Emperor Gojong]], nominated him as a Crown Prince of Korea as a descendant of the [[House of Yi]], the last ruling royal house of Korea during the [[Joseon dynasty]]. Following his nomination of Crown Prince, he announced plans to launch a investment fund for Korean entrepreneurs and establish a free coding school in Korea.\n\nHe also co-founded Mt. Gox Live which was acquired by Japan-based [[Mt. Gox]], then the world\u2019s leading Bitcoin exchange, and built their official mobile application. Mt. Gox closed in 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nLee was born and raised in Indianapolis, he says his parents never disclosed their royal relations, so he only learned about his connection through a passing reference from a relative. His father provided him with a computer when he was a child, which began interest in the internet, and he learning more about it through meeting people online on [[IRC]] chat rooms. He enrolled in [[Purdue University]] and transferred to [[University at Buffalo]], but eventually dropped out of school to start work on the internet.\n\nAndrew began his career as one of the two original System Administrators of AcmeShells.com, a major [[UNIX]] shell provider. After the company was acquired, he moved to Telemon and finally joined National Honey Almond, Inc (Blunt Wraps, Bluntville Cigars). While at NHA, as the [[Brand Manager]], He helped establish Bluntville as the best selling [[cigar]] on the East Coast.\n\nIn 2009, he built London Trust Media, Inc. LTM, a private holdings company. Lee founded Private Internet Access in 2010, which is the largest brand owned by London Trust Media.<ref>https://lifeboat.com/ex/bios.andrew.lee</ref> PIA was started because of Lee's interest in IRC, in order to protect one's [[IP address]] from exposure using an [[IRC bouncer]]. Eventually after being exposed to different industries, he realized it was time for internet privacy to go mainstream.<ref>https://www.linuxjournal.com/content/fight-control-andrew-lee-open-sourcing-pia</ref>\n\nHe also cofounded and sold many startups. One of his bitcoin ventures includes Mt. Gox North America, Inc., which was acquired by Tibanne Co. Ltd. in early 2011.\n\nAndrew contributes to online publications. Including FOL which is the online magazine of [[Rick Falkvinge]], the founder of the [[Pirate Party]].\n\nA few years before 2018 Lee met Emperor Yi Seok and the two got along so well Yi Seok decided to make him prince. A  \u201cpassing of the sword\u201d was held at the Crustacean Beverly Hills, a high-end Vietnamese seafood restaurant in Los Angeles. \u201cI will commit to the values of love, human rights, peace and freedom for humanity to the best of my ability,\u201d Lee swore on a [[ceremonial sword]]. Attendees included officials from [[Jeonju]], the family\u2019s ancestral home; Los Angeles city council members [[David Ryu]], [[Nury Martinez]] and [[Marqueece Harris-Dawson]]; and [[Bermuda]] Premier [[David Burt]].<ref>https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/andrew-lee-named-new-korean-crown-prince-300731986.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Purdue University alumni]]\n[[Category:House of Yi]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Bitcoin]]\n[[Category:Korean investors]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Las Vegas]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: a investment \u2192 an investment, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Lee_(entrepreneur)"}
{"title_page": "Hiram Walbridge", "text_new": "[[File:Hiram Walbridge.jpg|thumb|Hiram Walbridge, Congressman from New York]]\n'''Hiram Walbridge''' (February 2, 1821 \u2013 December 6, 1870) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]], cousin of [[Henry Sanford Walbridge]].\n\n==Life and career==\n[[File:Walbridge plot - Glenwood Cemetery - 2014-09-19.jpg|thumb|Grave of Hiram Walbridge.]]\nBorn in [[Ithaca, New York]], Walbridge moved to Ohio with his parents, who settled in [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] in 1836. He attended the public schools and the [[University of Ohio]] in [[Athens, Ohio|Athens]].\n\nWalbridge [[reading law|studied law]], was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1842 and commenced practice in Toledo. He was also an active member of the state militia, and was commissioned a [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in 1843. While living in Toledo, he served as a member of the board of aldermen.\n\nHe later moved to [[Buffalo, New York]], where he engaged in the mercantile business. He moved to [[New York City]] in 1847, where he continued his mercantile career.\n\nWalbridge was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[33rd United States Congress|Thirty-third]] Congress (March 4, 1853 \u2013 March 3, 1855). He declined to be a candidate for renomination in 1854. He supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] during the [[American Civil War]] and in 1862 was an unsuccessful Union candidate for election to the [[38th United States Congress|Thirty-eighth]] Congress.\n\nHe served as president of the International Commercial Convention held in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], July 11, 1865. Walbridge was elected as a delegate to the [[1866 National Union Convention]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\nHe died in New York City December 6, 1870. He was interred in [[Glenwood Cemetery (Washington, D.C.)|Glenwood Cemetery]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]{{sfn|Bailey|Morgan|Taylor|1986|page=2101}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bailey|first1=N. Louise|last2=Morgan|first2=Mary L.|last3=Taylor|first3=Carolyn R.|title=Biographical Directory of the South Carolina Senate: 1776-1985. Volume 1|location=Columbia, S.C.|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|date=1986|isbn=0872494799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|W000031}}\n*{{Findagrave|13196237}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= New York\n| district= 3\n| before= [[Emanuel B. Hart]]\n| after= [[Guy R. Pelton]]\n| years= 1853\u20131855 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walbridge, Hiram}}\n[[Category:1821 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American militia generals]]\n[[Category:Burials at Glenwood Cemetery (Washington, D.C.)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Unionists]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Ithaca, New York]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hiram Walbridge.jpg|thumb|Hiram Walbridge, Congressman from New York]]\n'''Hiram Walbridge''' (February 2, 1821 \u2013 December 6, 1870) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]], cousin of [[Henry Sanford Walbridge]].\n\n==Life and career==\n[[File:Walbridge plot - Glenwood Cemetery - 2014-09-19.jpg|thumb|Grave of Hiram Walbridge.]]\nBorn in [[Ithaca, New York]], Walbridge moved to Ohio with his parents, who settled in [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] in 1836. He attended the public schools and the [[University of Ohio]] in [[Athens, Ohio|Athens]].\n\nWalbridge [[reading law|studied law]], was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1842 and commenced practice in Toledo. He was also an active member of the state militia, and was commissioned a [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in 1843.\n\nHe later moved to [[Buffalo, New York]], where he engaged in the mercantile business and served as a member of the board of aldermen. He moved to [[New York City]] in 1847, where he continued his mercantile career.\n\nWalbridge was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[33rd United States Congress|Thirty-third]] Congress (March 4, 1853 \u2013 March 3, 1855). He declined to be a candidate for renomination in 1854. He supported the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] during the [[American Civil War]] and in 1862 was an unsuccessful Union candidate for election to the [[38th United States Congress|Thirty-eighth]] Congress.\n\nHe served as president of the International Commercial Convention held in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], July 11, 1865. Walbridge was elected as a delegate to the [[1866 National Union Convention]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\nHe died in New York City December 6, 1870. He was interred in [[Glenwood Cemetery (Washington, D.C.)|Glenwood Cemetery]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]{{sfn|Bailey|Morgan|Taylor|1986|page=2101}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bailey|first1=N. Louise|last2=Morgan|first2=Mary L.|last3=Taylor|first3=Carolyn R.|title=Biographical Directory of the South Carolina Senate: 1776-1985. Volume 1|location=Columbia, S.C.|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|date=1986|isbn=0872494799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|W000031}}\n*{{Findagrave|13196237}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state= New York\n| district= 3\n| before= [[Emanuel B. Hart]]\n| after= [[Guy R. Pelton]]\n| years= 1853\u20131855 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walbridge, Hiram}}\n[[Category:1821 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New 